Sure, below is an example on how to use interrupts and ISR (Interrupt Service Routine) in Arduino Mega:

```cpp
const int INTERRUPT_PIN = 2; // The pin to attach the interrupt

volatile int interruptCounter = 0;

void setup() {
  Serial.begin(9600);
  attachInterrupt(digitalPinToInterrupt(INTERRUPT_PIN), ISR, CHANGE);
}

void loop() {
  // Main code here
}

void ISR() {
  interruptCounter++;
  Serial.print("Interrupt Counter: ");
  Serial.println(interruptCounter);
}
```

In this example, an interrupt is attached to pin 2 using `attachInterrupt()` function, which will trigger the `ISR()` function when the interrupt condition is met (in this case, a CHANGE in the digital signal). The `ISR()` function increments the interrupt counter and prints the counter value to the serial monitor.

Remember that in ISR functions, you should keep the code as short and fast as possible to prevent blocking other critical code execution.

