I believe you are asking about performing a task immediately in Arduino. You can achieve this by placing the code that you want to execute immediately outside the `setup()` or `loop()` functions. For example:

```cpp
void setup() {
  Serial.begin(9600);
}

void loop() {
  // Main code here
}

void performTaskImmediately() {
  // Code to be executed immediately
}

void setup() {
  Serial.begin(9600);
  performTaskImmediately(); // Call the function to perform the task immediately
}

void loop() {
  // Main code here
}
```

In the above example, the `performTaskImmediately()` function is called within the `setup()` function to execute the task immediately after the initialization. This way, the task will be performed once at the beginning of the program.

If you have a specific task or action that you want to perform immediately and continuously, you can place it within the `loop()` function to have it executed in every iteration of the loop.

